# Code Standards

All generated code must follow these guidelines.

## Performance & Resource

- **No memory leaks** — close connections, cancel contexts, release resources; avoid unbounded growth
- **High performance** — minimize allocations, avoid unnecessary copies, use pooling where appropriate
- **Lightweight** — keep dependencies minimal; avoid heavy abstractions that add overhead

## Organization

- **Separate files and folders by domain** — structure by business/feature domain, not technical type

- **String queries as constants/vars** — put SQL, GraphQL, or other query strings in a dedicated file (e.g. `queries.go`, `queries.sql`) within the domain; use `const` or `var`, avoid inline literals

## Proto

- **Separate proto files by domain** — one proto file per domain/feature; avoid God proto files
- **Keep each file clear and focused** — one responsibility per file; use `import` to share messages across files
- **No monolithic proto** — split large `.proto` files into smaller, domain-scoped files (e.g. `route.proto`, `service.proto`, `auth.proto`)

## Functions & Algorithms

- **Keep the algorithm in a function small** — extract complex logic into smaller, well-named functions

## Frontend (React)

- Follow **naming conventions** (PascalCase components, `use` prefix for hooks, etc.)
- Use **React best practices** and **design patterns**
- Functional components, custom hooks, composition
- See `react-guidelines` for details (applies when editing `ui/**/*.tsx`)

## Backend (Go)

- Follow **naming conventions** (packages lowercase, interfaces `er` suffix, files snake_case, etc.)
- Follow **SOLID principles** (SRP, OCP, LSP, ISP, DIP)
- Use **programming by interface** — depend on abstractions, inject dependencies
- Apply appropriate **design patterns** (Repository, Factory, Strategy, Adapter, Options)
- See `backend-guidelines` for details (applies when editing `internal/**/*.go`, `pkg/**/*.go`)
